label("$\frac{\pi}{4}$", (pi/4,0), S);

label("$h(\theta)$", (pi/2,1), N);
label("$\frac{v^2}{2g}$", (0,0), SW);
[/asy]

Note that $h(\theta)$ is symmetric about $\theta = 90^\circ.$  Furthermore, $h(\theta)$ is increasing on the interval $0^\circ \le \theta \le 90^\circ,$ and decreasing on the interval $90^\circ \le \theta \le 180^\circ.$

The area we seek is
\[2 \int_0^{\pi/2} h(\theta) \, d \theta = \frac{v^4}{2g^2} \int_0^{\pi/2} \sin^2 \theta \, d \theta.\]We can evaluate the integral as follows:
\begin{align*}
\int_0^{\pi/2} \sin^2 \theta \, d \theta &= \int_0^{\pi/2} \frac{1 - \cos 2 \theta}{2} \, d \theta \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \left[ \theta - \frac{1}{2} \sin 2 \theta \right]_0^{\pi/2} \\
&= \frac{\pi}{4}.
\end{align*}Therefore, the area of the region is $\boxed{\frac{\pi}{4}} \cdot \frac{v^4}{g^2}.$

The highest point of the trajectory occurs when the vertical velocity is 0.  This occurs when $vt \sin \theta - gt^2/2 = 0,$ or $t = 2v \sin \theta/g.$  Substituting into the equation for $y,$ we get
\[y = \frac{v^2 \sin^2 \theta}{g} - \frac{2v^2 \sin^2 \theta}{g} = -\frac{v^2 \sin^2 \theta}{g}.\]Thus, the highest point of the trajectory is $(v^2/g) (\sin^2 \theta, -1).$

